Headlines.Headline: One Death Reported After Minneapolis Explosion

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Caroline Porter At least one person is dead following an explosion and three-alarm fire that destroyed a building in south Minneapolis on New Year's Day, according to city fire department officials. The victim was found inside the building Thursday and transported to the county medical examiner's office. The local fire chief previously had said that two people remained unaccounted for following the incident. It is unclear if that has since changed. The three-floor building, which housed a grocery store and apartment units, is under investigation by city officials who are searching for clues and removing rubble.

PARAGRAPH.#text: Investors may be heading into 2012 with more questions than answers  about how Europe's debt crisis will work out but German lending giant  Deutsche Bank AG is putting a brave face on things.Deutsche is  forecasting another growth year for global merger and acquisition, or  M&A, activity as companies take advantage of cheap valuations. Headlines.Headline: Newswatch: Summary of top market, business news

PARAGRAPH.#text:
WASHINGTON(CBS.MW) -- The stock market is well off its highs. Is it enough of a
    slowdown for the Fed? Economists say the Fed is looking for another month or three of
    softer growth and moderate inflation before it can really believe that the economy is
    heading in for a soft landing. Most analysts are still looking for the Fed to raise its
    Federal funds by 25 basis points again on June 29. Further signs of a slowdown will be
    hard to find in the coming week's data. The National Association of Purchasing Management
    index comes out on Thursday, and the May jobs report comes out on Friday. Neither report
    is likely to show any softness, economists said.

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Newswatch: Summary of top market, business news

PARAGRAPH.#text:
NEW YORK (CBS.MW) -- The equity market ended close to unchanged levels in a
    session characterized by listless, rangebound trading as investors remained nervous about
    upcoming economic data and rising interest rates. With a long weekend ahead, market
    participants were even less willing to take on additional risk and kept positions close to
    the vest throughout Friday's session. Inside the market, brokerage stocks extended
    Thursday's losses as concerns continue to mount that the slow IPO calendar and diminishing
    trading volumes will take a significant bite into the earnings of Wall Street firms. The
    broader market saw the greatest weakness in the biotech, paper, oil service and paper
    sectors while utility stocks climbed. Internet and computer hardware stocks were the
    hardest hit sectors in the technology arena. The Dow Industrials shed 24.68 points, or 0.2
    percent, to 10,299.24. The Nasdaq Composite lost 0.20 point to 3,205.15 while the Nasdaq
    100 index, which encompasses the largest Nasdaq stocks by market capitalization, inched up
    2.27 points, or 0.1 percent, to 3,101.55.

    "Panic of 2000." Never before in American history have we had so many funds and
    stocks with triple-digit returns (100 percent plus). In fact, over 170 funds doubled (or
    better) their investors' money in the past year. Hey, did your funds double your money
    last year? Even return 25 percent? Tech is the winner. You'd be a millionaire today if you
    put just $1,000 in a tech stock like Dell a decade ago. Heady stuff, huh!
